    <h2>Limitations and Challenges</h2>

    <div class="callout warning">
      <div class="callout-title">⚠️ Known Issues</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hallucinations:</strong> Generate plausible but false information</li>
        <li><strong>Lack of grounding:</strong> No connection to real-world facts</li>
        <li><strong>Reasoning limitations:</strong> Struggle with complex logic and math</li>
        <li><strong>Outdated knowledge:</strong> Training data has cutoff date</li>
        <li><strong>Inconsistency:</strong> Different responses to same question</li>
        <li><strong>Bias:</strong> Reflect biases in training data</li>
        <li><strong>No true understanding:</strong> Pattern matching, not comprehension</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Best Practices</h2>

    <div class="callout success">
      <div class="callout-title">✅ Effective LLM Usage</div>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Clear instructions:</strong> Be specific and unambiguous</li>
        <li><strong>Provide context:</strong> Include relevant background information</li>
        <li><strong>Use examples:</strong> Few-shot prompting improves performance</li>
        <li><strong>Break down tasks:</strong> Decompose complex problems</li>
        <li><strong>Verify outputs:</strong> Always fact-check critical information</li>
        <li><strong>Iterate prompts:</strong> Refine based on responses</li>
        <li><strong>Set temperature:</strong> Lower for factual, higher for creative</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Summary</h2>

    <div class="callout success">
      <div class="callout-title">✅ Key Takeaways</div>
      <ul>
        <li>LLMs are Transformer-based models trained to predict the next token at scale.</li>
        <li>Practical systems typically combine pre-training, supervised fine-tuning, and preference-based alignment (e.g., RLHF).</li>
        <li>Scale and data/compute choices affect what models can learn and how reliably they perform.</li>
        <li>Prompting and context design strongly influence output quality.</li>
        <li>Limitations (e.g., hallucinations, grounding, and reasoning gaps) require verification and safeguards.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What is a large language model, in plain English?</h3>
    <p>An LLM is a neural network trained to predict the next word in a sequence, across billions of text examples. Through training at scale, it learns grammar, facts, reasoning patterns, and how to follow instructions — without being explicitly programmed for any of these tasks.</p>

    <h3>How do GPT-4o, Claude, and Gemini differ?</h3>
    <p>All three are capable general-purpose LLMs from different organizations (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google). They differ in context window size, multimodal capabilities, pricing, licensing, and safety training approaches. As of mid-2026, the gap between leading models has narrowed significantly, making practical factors — cost, API reliability, and data privacy terms — as important as raw capability.</p>

    <h3>What does “hallucination” mean and how serious is it?</h3>
    <p>Hallucination means the model generates plausible-sounding but incorrect information — fabricated facts, wrong dates, or non-existent references. Seriousness depends on use case: high-stakes applications (medical, legal, financial) need systematic verification and grounding (see <a href={`${base}/chapters/08-rag`}>Chapter 8: RAG</a>). Creative or brainstorming uses are far less sensitive to this risk.</p>

    <h3>When does an LLM need fine-tuning vs. a better prompt?</h3>
    <p>Try prompting first — most use cases are solved by clear instructions, examples, and context. Fine-tuning helps when you need consistent output format, domain-specific vocabulary, or behavior that is hard to specify in a prompt. It requires labeled training data and is harder to maintain as the base model updates. See <a href={`${base}/chapters/09-fine-tuning`}>Chapter 9: Fine-Tuning</a> for the full trade-off.</p>

    <h3>What is RLHF and why does it matter?</h3>
    <p>Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) is the alignment technique that turns a raw text predictor into a helpful assistant. Human raters rank model outputs, a reward model learns their preferences, and the LLM is optimized to score higher on that reward. ChatGPT, Claude, and most commercial LLMs use RLHF or a close variant of it.</p>

